        <section class="notion">
          <div id="ne_c-r">
            <div class="main-wt">
              <h4 class="main-wt-title">Contraction - Relaxation</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Isometric Contraction</strong> - Exercises that do not change muscle length. It is a
                  joint-free exercise. Enduring exercise is a representative example. ex) 플랭크, 플란체</li>
                <li><strong>Isotonic Contraction</strong> - Exercises that do change muscle length. There is
                  <strong>Eccentric Contraction</strong>and <strong>Concentric Contraction</strong>
                </li>
                <li style="border-bottom: 1px solid #28282B; width: 20rem; margin: 0 auto;"></li>
                <li>Eccentric Contraction - An exercise that stretches the muscle. Movement occurs in the same direction
                  as the resistance(gravity). Increased range of motion of muscles, effective in preventing injuries ex)
                  Lying triceps extension, Pilates
                </li>
                <li>Concentric contraction - Movement that brings the muscles together. Movement occurs in the direction
                  opposite to resistance(gravity). ex) cable push down</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>


          <div id="ne_o-i">
            <div class="main-wt">
              <h4 class="main-wt-title">Origin - Insertion</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Origin</strong> - where muscles start</li>
                <li><strong>Insertion</strong> - where muscles ends</li>
                <li>Muscles move from the insertion to the origin</li>
                <li>The closer the muscle is to the origin from the insertion, the more resistance training it is, and
                  the farther the insertion from the origin is, becomes stretching</li>
                <li>ex) When the arms are brought together and the chest is gathered, the insertion is close to the
                  origin, and this becomes a resistance training. When the arms are opened, the chest is stretched, and
                  the insertion and the origin are moved away, which is stretching</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>


          <div id="ne_p-d">
            <div class="main-wt">
              <h4 class="main-wt-title">Proximal - Distal</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Proximal</strong> - closer to the center of the body</li>
                <li><strong>Distal</strong> - closer to the end of the body</li>
                <li>This is a relative concept</li>
                <br>
                <li>Proximal exercise is more difficult than distal exercise</li>
                <li>The number of mobilized joints is large, the size of muscles is large, and the degree of
                  neurodevelopment is different</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>


          <div id="ne_r">
            <div class="main-wt">
              <h4 class="main-wt-title">Role</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Agonist</strong> - It is used predominantly and uses the greatest force. is a single muscle
                </li>
                <li><strong>Synergist</strong> - Helps and assists the prime mover. more than one muscle</li>
                <li><strong>Antagonist</strong> - A muscle that opposes the Agonist. works in the opposite direction
                </li>
                <li>Agonists and synergists are used for concentric contractions, and antagonists are used for eccentric
                  contractions</li>
                <li>Opposing muscles support the joint</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>


          <div id="ne_c">
            <div class="main-wt">
              <h4 class="main-wt-title">Chain Movement</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Opened Kinetic Chain Exercise</strong>(OKC) - The distal part performs the movement
                  function. The proximal part is responsible for stability. limb movement. <strong>Hands and feet
                    move</strong> ex) Bench Press</li>
                <li><strong>Closed Kinetic Chain Exercise</strong>(CKC) - The proximal part performs the movement
                  function. The distal part is responsible for stability. body moves. <strong>Hand and Feet
                    fixed</strong> ex) Push Up</li>
                <li>CKC exercises are effective in strengthening the overall muscles. CKC exercises have low load on
                  joints and high stability because antagonist and agonist muscles contract simultaneously</li>
                <li>OKC exercises are effective for strengthening(isolating) individual muscles. Because OKC exercises
                  use only one muscle, the load on the joints is relatively high</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>


          <div id="ne_a-c">
            <div class="main-wt no-border">
              <h4 class="main-wt-title">Anabolism - Catabolism</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Anabolism</strong> - The action of synthesizing small molecules into larger molecules.
                  Energy is released(exotherm)</li>
                <li><strong>Catabolism</strong> - The action of breaking down large molecules into smaller molecules.
                  Energy is absorbed(endothermic)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>


